{
    "level": "A2",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn to use <strong>Present Continuous</strong> for <strong>future arrangements and organized plans</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "ARRANGEMENT",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "<strong>Present Continuous</strong> often means that the event is already arranged or organized:",
            "example": "I am meeting Anna tomorrow."
        },
        {
            "label": "TIME MARKER",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "A <strong>future time marker</strong> usually makes the meaning clear:",
            "example": "tonight, tomorrow, next week, at 6"
        },
        {
            "label": "NOT EVERY FUTURE",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "For a spontaneous decision or a simple prediction, <strong>will</strong> or <strong>be going to</strong> is often better.",
            "example": "I will answer it. / I am going to study tonight."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Formula",
    "intro": "The form is the same as for actions happening now, but the context gives it a future meaning.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Affirmative",
            "title": "am / is / are + V-ing",
            "subtitle": "We are leaving at 7."
        },
        {
            "label": "Negative",
            "title": "am not / is not / are not + V-ing",
            "subtitle": "She is not working tomorrow."
        },
        {
            "label": "Question",
            "title": "Am / Is / Are + subject + V-ing?",
            "subtitle": "Are you meeting them tonight?"
        },
        {
            "label": "Time markers",
            "title": "tomorrow / tonight / next week / on Friday",
            "subtitle": "without a marker, the future meaning may be unclear"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. When it works best",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Arrangements and meetings",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "This form works well when the event is already <strong>organized</strong>: there is a time, place, ticket, or agreement.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "We are having dinner with Paul on Friday.",
                    "ua": "We are having dinner with Paul on Friday."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I am flying to Berlin next Monday.",
                    "ua": "I am flying to Berlin next Monday."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They are meeting the client at 10.",
                    "ua": "They are meeting the client at 10."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "A time marker makes the future clear",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "A marker such as <strong>tomorrow</strong> or <strong>at 6</strong> helps show that the action is not happening now.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She is working late tomorrow.",
                    "ua": "She is working late tomorrow."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Are you staying in tonight?",
                    "ua": "Are you staying in tonight?"
                },
                {
                    "en": "I am not seeing him next week.",
                    "ua": "I am not seeing him next week."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Compare it with will and be going to",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "<strong>Present Continuous</strong> stresses organization; <strong>will</strong> often means a decision now, and <strong>be going to</strong> often means intention or plan.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The phone is ringing. I will answer it.",
                    "ua": "The phone is ringing. I will answer it."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I am meeting the doctor at 4.",
                    "ua": "I am meeting the doctor at 4."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I am going to read more this summer.",
                    "ua": "I am going to read more this summer."
                }
            ],
            "note": "This form is especially natural when the plan is already arranged."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Leaving out the verb be.",
            "wrong": "I meeting Sam tomorrow.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I am meeting Sam tomorrow.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Using Present Continuous for a spontaneous decision.",
            "wrong": "The phone is ringing. I am answering it.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">The phone is ringing. I will answer it.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "No future context.",
            "wrong": "We are having dinner.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">We are having dinner tomorrow.</span> <span class=\"text-slate-500\">(if you mean the future)</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Present Continuous for Future</strong> describes already arranged future actions.",
        "Form: <em>am / is / are + V-ing</em>.",
        "A time marker is usually needed: <em>tomorrow, tonight, next week, at 6</em>.",
        "<strong>Will</strong> more often expresses a decision made at the moment of speaking.",
        "<strong>Be going to</strong> often stresses intention or plan, while <strong>Present Continuous</strong> stresses a concrete arrangement."
    ]
}

